#include <stdio.h>

void bubbleSort(int arr[], int n) {
  int i, j, temp;
  for (i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
    for (j = 0; j < n - i - 1; j++) {
      if (arr[j] > arr[j + 1]) {
        // Swap arr[j] and arr[j+1]
        temp = arr[j];
        arr[j] = arr[j + 1];
        arr[j + 1] = temp;
      }
    }
  }
}

int main() {
  int arr[] = {64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90};
  int n = sizeof(arr) / sizeof(arr[0]);

  printf("Unsorted array: \n");
  for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    printf("%d ", arr[i]);
  }

  bubbleSort(arr, n);

  printf("\nSorted array: \n");
  for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    printf("%d ", arr[i]);
  }
  printf("\n");

  return 0;
}
```

**Explanation:**

1. **`bubbleSort(int arr[], int n)` function:**
   - Takes an integer array `arr` and its size `n` as input.
   - Uses two nested loops to iterate through the array.
   - The outer loop (`i`) runs from 0 to `n-1`.
   - The inner loop (`j`) runs from 0 to `n-i-1`.
   - Inside the inner loop, it compares adjacent elements (`arr[j]` and `arr[j+1]`).
   - If they are in the wrong order, it swaps them using a temporary variable `temp`.

2. **`main()` function:**
   - Declares an integer array `arr` with some unsorted values.
   - Calculates the size of the array `n`.
   - Prints the unsorted array.
   - Calls the `bubbleSort()` function to sort the array.
   - Prints the sorted array.

**How Bubble Sort Works:**

Bubble sort repeatedly steps through the list, compares adjacent elements, and swaps them if they are in the wrong order. The largest element "bubbles" to the end of the list in each pass. This process is repeated until the entire list is sorted.

**Time Complexity:**

- Best case: O(n) - when the array is already sorted.
- Average case: O(n^2)
- Worst case: O(n^2)

Bubble sort is generally not efficient for large datasets due to its quadratic time complexity.

